 >

 > will check home network by sending to modem at%cereg? and if we add
 > another swi function we will resend again at%cereg? so we can just
 > send it once and decide if network is connected depending cereg
 > status

I am not talking about another CEREG? to be sent but to replace
if( stat == CREG_STAT_REGISTERED_HOME)
by 
if((stat == CREG_STAT_REGISTERED_HOME) || (stat ==CREG_STAT_REGISTERED_ROAMING))

- no issue with modified code

comments.message:
need to remove this macth we need just to check quoted string else comeback to params to check the end of the string

in this example at+clac="""\r\n it will not check quoted string if \
Check a valid string if true then concatenate else go to <PARAMS>

Need to check if <"> is at the beginning or preceded by <,> otherwise a non valid argument will be allowed 

example :

if aaaaa is matched and then followed by <"> then it go to check for quoted so aaaaa"bbbbbb" will be ok or it is not valid and num_params need to be -1

Need to check if character except <,\"> is at the beginning or preceded by <,> otherwise a non valid argument will be allowed 

example :

if parser match "aaaaaa" and followed by bbbbb then the parser match "aaaaaa"bbbbb : it is not a valid argument (need to be preceded  by <,> ) and num_pramas need to be -1

match \" : 
-- if a \" is at the beginning of the <PARAMS> or if it is preceded by \, then go to <QUOTED> to check if the string is quoted 

-- Else terminate : The params is not valid then num_params = -1

match all Except whats is between []: 
-- if the matched pattern is at the beginning of the <PARAMS> or if it is preceded by \, then add extracted pattern to the list of parameters 

-- Else terminate : The params is not valid then num_params = -1

comments.message: Not used anymore, should be deleted

How did you choose this value? As far as I remember, 10 seconds was the timer to check preconditions (network coverage), but it is really necessary to wait 10 seconds before checking swiserver is alive?
"A priori"  this value seems too high
What value do you recommend ? I followed the "wait for lwm2m" one

if swiserver is not alive (crashed for example), fotam will never be able to start -> not possible to update the FW anymore
-> in order to recover from a faulty update, it should be possible to update the FW
-> fotam should not wait indefinitely for swiserver
we can set a number of finite attempts. What do you suggest ?
Even if swiserver is launched after fotam, I guess 1 minute should be enough

Please do not modify the initial Altair indentation
+ modified behaviour from Altair code should be flagged NOSWI in order to ease integration

- I will try to keep the original indentation, but code is slightly different
- if I put NOSWI, this will be very complicated. We just moved the code from the "case" below to the "case" above. Putting NOSWI will lead to duplicated lines

Regarding indentation, my remark was only about usage of whitespaces instead of tabs used in Altair code. Of course if a new condition is added, indentation should be modified.

Regarding NOSWI, I understand the side-effect and duplicated lines (but not embedded), but it is already the case in plenty of locations in Altair source code we modified. Without flags  integration work would be too complex
this code should not be executed in case upgMgrSmm.m_cfg.m_testMode value is 1
We do not use test mode, and I don't know the side effects ot this (untested). I can try to keep this code but it will be untested
Do not understand your point: this code was already present before and also not tested -> we should keep the same behaviour as before is this mode is used

My previous comment remains valid: 
"Regarding NOSWI, I understand the side-effect and duplicated lines (but not embedded), but it is already the case in plenty of locations in Altair source code we modified. Without flags integration work would be too complex"

comments.message: The function is correct but I would have prefer if you tried to mutualize with existing READ command.

That's a very bad idea.

This function is ran from SWISERVER code, and maybe from a command handler handled by SWISERVER itself. AT servers are not reentrant. This means that you cannot launch a new command if the current command has not returned (you'll get ERROR because the current is not cancelable).

As a rule, SWISERVER AT command handlers MUST NOT emit AT commands that are handled by SWISERVER itself.
No I can't: KLWM2MSEL_get_active_instance() does not return the status of the notification

this is code block #2.

These 2 blocks could be refactored to be a single function.
Then you can print the line to answers to AT+KLWMTOMSEL? or extract the active_instance.

comments.message:
reformat: Put a short description here:
"Check for invalid time format"
Error code 50 is only used by Altair, please use either 3 or 4
avoid using error 50, never used in our developments
consistency: add space before and after

NO. you can leave this brace here, but remove the indentation.
or you can put the brace after the if.
missing error message LOGE to tell what is the error.
wrong. check first that params[0] is not NULL. in AT commands, parameters may be NULL
NO. only one trace_leave is allowed. That's the aim of putting a goto label. Must be refactored.
only one return is allowed. refactor.

wrong. trace_leave must be the very last function call before returning. this way we are sure the function did not block.
here you're not sure intercept_cmd() will not block after you've written that you exited your function.

comments.message: this does not make sense since SWIURC is a generic URC sending command. As such you cannot put inside it code that triggers the URC depending on <args>

I don't understand the aim. Are you cheking that it is a number ? why ?
You should rather check that the string starts with a + for an URC.

I check that the argument is a string (so, not a number). I don't like the check with the '+', because if we want to send with a '%' it will not work. I can add other allowed characters, but a simple check on a string appears me as a sufficient check.
Why being a number is problematic ?
+SWIURC is enough to identify the origin. Do not disclose intellectual property.

wrong. if ptr=aaaaa"hello"aaaa, pBeg will be at ptr+6 and pEnd at ptr+10. this does not do what you intended to.

Use is_dquoted_str() from utils.h
OK. Was a copy paste from +NVBU=send_urc...

beware of OVERFLOW ! ptr has a size of strlen(params[0]). even if ptr has "" eliminated, this will overflow because you should have allocated strlen()+1 for the \0.
if ptr does not have "", same price: overflow again.
So we also a bug in +NVBU=send_urc
I don't know if you should disclose the URC. Such URCs are for internal purposes and are not routed to default input. So printing it in the logs is not advisable. Use LOGD for example.
ALWAYS prefix with the command name. In analyzing logs, this will be help a lot in separating the command flows
Where are the URC args ????? If args are not supported, just remove them.
please tell why being a number is problematic.

Because URC with a number is a nonsense. You display strings, which can contain numbers but it's a string.
Furthermore, strchr will do a segfault if parameter is a number.
not needed. is_dquoted_str ensures that string starts and ends with ". So no need to "search" for quotes: they are at the beginning and at the end.
so really don't want to show +SWIURC ?
I find that handle_plus_SWIURC is easier to debug than just +SWIURC, no?

I'm sorry but that won't work because you'll get the terminating " from cmd->params[0]. Did you test ?

Please also check the length: StringLength-1. Doc says that it must include the terminating \0.
Yes it works. Now you know why I prefer strcat ;-)

comments.message:
MAX_PENDING_URCS
a little bit short to my opinion. There is NVBU, KSUP and soon to come WDSI: 0.
I would set it to 8

I have another big concern regarding this: if we queue unsolicited while atsw is not connected, then no longer send unsolicited when its connected, the queued unsollicited will remain unsent.

I would suggest using the "connect_cb()" callback which is installed on servers to achieve sending of queued unsolicited. "connect_cb()" is called whenever a client is connected to us.
That's what is done in function client_connect_cb in server.c file

why did you choose to use a flag here (and keep the code) whereas you did choose to delete the function in .h?
-> homogeneity

I wanted to use a flag here and in the .h, but I forgot to erase the comments on the prototypes in .h (previously added during my dev). I update the .h to uncomment the prototypes in order to keep the homogeneity.
Please precise the flag name in order to avoid scrolling back to the #ifdef / #ifndef
should be better to use strlen instead of a magical number
is it necessary to check again if previous condition is met and validParam is already set to TRUE?
Yes, because ATH\r\n is not detected as valid parameter by the previous condition. Here I use strlen to replace the magical number.
ERROR or AT_CB_RET_CME_ERR_3 (cf current code of ATH_SwiCb)?
AT_CB_RET_CME_ERR_3 was introduced in a delivery after my last repo synchronisation. After the repo sync I need to add that error in both ATH_SwiCb.

[ALT1210-364] Management of extended error codes into confmanager

Basic management of error codes in CNF/GCS/SWI

Resolves: ALT1210-364 ALT1210-363 ALT1210-362
Change-Id: I1865ca18997269318ce2d94a0abba357a5246048
commits.subject: [ALT1210-364] Management of extended error codes into confmanager

comments.message: remove here and put it in Makefile's CFLAGS

repalce with CRLF ? or response_terminator_char ?
No need to multiply the names for the same thing
is this the max specified by the standard ?
already known as response_terminator_char in this server.
not needed. In fact it is better to omit it, since C will automatically take previous entry+1.

I don't understand why you need to enumerate all possible error cases ...
This is definitely not good at all and a better more generic way to achieve this is needed

Personal opinion: I would have kept the defines, and added a new field in at_rsp_t (for example: err_code).

#define AT_RSP_ERROR     -1
#define AT_RSP_CME_ERR_3 3
...

rsp->status = AT_RSP_ERROR   /* not changed */
rsp->err_code = AT_RSP_CME_ERR_3 /* added */

this will lead to a similar behavior than the one in libc, where functions return non zero code (or -1) in case of failure, and there an additional "errno" variable to know the exact error.

I do understand your proposition.
I would rather prefer to keep now this dev which is similar to the one done on gcserver and confmanager. And this enum of errors has been copied to other products such as HL8.
I do not understand this sentence
Please use a formula to compute this if the result is constant.
you do not need to specify the size. Just put [] and for the compiler this is fine since it can be computed at compile-time. You'll save yourself out-of-bounds errors and missing initializers.
I'm afraid we must merge this function with Pol's parset_at_rsp() (see atcmd.h)
just a remark: the right formula for computing an array size is sizeof(array)/sizeof(array[0])

commits.commitMessage:
[ALT1210-374] [FOTA] Depackaging of delta package received by the AV server

Augment Altair's FOTA Manager by Sierra's handling of DWL files
Changes include:
  - Moving the LWM2M download directory from /upload to /tmp.
    This is necessary as we need to extract the DWL into /upload
    and this latter usually cannot contain both DWL and extracted UA
    because of insufficient space
  - Introducing the alt-fotamgr.Update.UADirectory UCI entry that points
    to /upload
  - Introducing DWL packet extraction routines, CRC verification and
    AV server signature verification
  - Linking against libcrypto
Note: CRC computations use open source code from zlib.

Resolves: ALT1210-374
Change-Id: I71d0c7cd6bb11f2d28f6f32aba2d388c64d6fcb9
commits.subject: [ALT1210-374] [FOTA] Depackaging of delta package received by the AV server

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Not gone through the whole code but important remarks:

- I'm against using the epoll interface because it is Linux specific and is not portable. Using select() is POSIX and has more chance to be portable.

- why the hell all the functions are prefixed by SWI ? Is it necessary and useful ? they should rather be prefixed by (for example) gpio_....(). why swi_gpio.c/h and not gpio_utils.c for example, like it has been done for otp_utils.c ?

- SWISERVER starts to become unmaitainable because of different identifier naming schemes. UpperCase vs LowerCase vs CamelCase vs Mixed_with_dashes ... Is there a rule for this ? It needs urgent cleanup.

- Altair code is not a good code and should not be copied. We should write clean code for SWISERVER.

- Also a note about using the constants SUCCESS and FAILURE. They should not be used when calling POSIX functions like:
  ret = epoll_create(...)
  if ( ret == FAILURE )

this is wrong because POSIX says -1 on error. You should test against -1 (or write if (!ret)) because we cannot guarantee that the constant FAILURE will always have the value -1 (that's the primary reason why we use a #define for it: to be able to change its value easily).

Also introduction of these two constants added confusion because some functions say that they return 0 on success and others say SUCCESS on success. And we must check the function documentation to write the right test and this is not homogeneous.

ambiguous message. Indeed the CPOF command IS supported. try a more explicit message: "Invalid number of args. Expected: none" for example.
it depends on if the "other" server returns a response before of after executing the poweroff. what's the behavior ?
you don't need ERROR: you are already using LOGE
unmeaningful message for a customer: say that you failed to poweroff the machine.
same remarks as above regarding messages, LOGE, ...
not needed as sizeof(reply)-1  guarantees that the latest byte of reply will be null terminated as per its initialization

It would be more readable with another variable name and with an appropriate comment.

comments.message: shouldn't you use your logX() functions here ?
zero timeout is not recommended at all. the script may exit before having received the response. Use 'usleep' for very short sleeps
fw_printenv is quite slow. consider saving the value in a variable
remove handle_. it was an error for the previous ones
If I use sprintf I have to extract first a part of the string from pbeg with the correct size. Not sure that's will be better.

you're using LOGW but printing an ERROR.
use: LOGE("+NVBU: .....");

WRONG !!! you're locking the mutex in a thread and release it in another thread. THIS IS FORBIDDEN ! It is undefined behavior. see man page:
" If a thread attempts to unlock a mutex that it has
  not locked or a mutex which is unlocked, undefined behavior results.".
no goto end ? no mutex release ? you'll deadlock

cryptic message for a user.
why the mutex can be locked at this stage ?
why is it not at the end ?
do not print messages in utility functions. Let the caller print whatever it wants

wrong. when the timeout is zero you take the risk of exiting at.sh before having received the response. The subsequent usleep will do nothing against that.

You have to copy the contents of at.sh here are change the internal sleep by usleep.
WARNING: you have already locked the semaphore. You must unlock it here

comments.message: now you have a parse function available ;-) However no problem with this version because it was not committed at time
this is the base64 algorithm. Nothing more to say here other than that.
Why do not use uciGetSetOption function?

The problem with this function is that it prints logs by itself despite it is a utility function. This is bad programming practice: utility functions should never print logs by themselves and rather return an error code. The caller is responsible of displaying something or ignoring it.

To sum up, I did it like that to control what is printed in the logs.
Why do not use uciGetSetOption function?
Could be more readable if all the "checks" had been deported in another function
why ? this is the body of the handler and it is part of the handler to check its args

We should have the same behavior in the swiapp: is a bad user input a LOGE or a LOGW? You put at the same trace level a common user input error with a critical internal error to generate an encryption key.
Idem for cases bellow.

I use LOGE (error) for critical errors: this means that we cannot continue.

I use LOGW (warnings) for recoverable errors: we can continue. For example the AT+CLAC handler which returns an empty list if clac.txt is not found.

So this is consistent (at least here).
It is more readable to use defines instead of values for mode and itemid.
You can use the new defines

commits.commitMessage:
ALT1210-124: Addition of parsing facilities into swiserver application

Implementation of a "mini parser" to easily extract string information
from AT command received in swiserver.
- Take an AT answer string of type 'COMMAND\r\nBODY\r\nOK\r\n'
  or 'COMMAND\r\nBODY\r\nERROR\r\n' and extract the BODY between '\r\n'
- The body can had several lines separated by a '\r\n'
- Each line could be extracted in a struct array
- Each parameter in a line could be extracted individually

Resolves: ALT1210-124
Change-Id: Ifc6ec575538c70af169daef6b0051b03abd10392

commits.commitMessage:
ALT1210-28: Template for new Sierra applications

Provide an ATSWITCH skeleton server application. It is capable of:
  - Listening to incoming AT commands from ATSWITCH
  - Parsing these commands and building AST trees
  - Processing the commands
  - Sending back answers to ATSWITCH
  - Forwarding commands to ATSWITCH

A CSV ATSWITCH configuration file is provided as an example, it
accepts the AT+SIERRA command

In order to compile this sample server, add its .mk file to
makefiles/applications.mk

Resolves: ALT1210-28
Change-Id: I6eb96634b780200ca0bad1a5ede50c6a9ae13ebb
commits.subject: ALT1210-28: Template for new Sierra applications

commits.commitMessage:
ALT1210-27: Multi NVM generation

Improve Altair's build system so as to enable multiple
board flavors (called variants).

This results in the generation of a single rootfs filesystem and
multiple NVM images. Each NVM image matches a board variant.

The following main changes are introduced:
  - The config/bsp_files/<board> directory MUST contain subdirectories.
    Each subdirectory represents a board variant. BSP files must be
    put inside config/bsp_files/<board>/<variant> now.

    Boards for which variants are not applicable must also have
    a generic variant (for example the variant "all")

  - The Linux flash script scripts/flash-all-sflash.sh now accepts
    these additional arguments:

    * --lsnvm     : lists all available NVM images
    * --nvmselect : interactive selection of an NVM image to flash
    * --nvmfile   : command line selection of an NVM image to flash

    Both --nvmselect and --nvmfile selections are saved to the
    flash config file (scripts/.flashall.conf). Behavior is similar
    to --dtb* options

Resolves: ALT1210-27
Change-Id: Id233c39802dd171d7eae88bd16f9e2ef311b6e1f
commits.subject: ALT1210-27: Multi NVM generation

ALT1210-7: Dummy AT commands

The Dummy Commands package includes:
- A first set of AT commands consists of AT commands that answers "OK" if parameters are ok:
  => ATB, AT\N, ATL, ATM, ATS6, ATS8, ATS10, ATN
- A second set of AT commands consists of AT commands that are linked to voice.
  As there is no voice on this project, but for compatibility with existing
  initialization sequences, there should answer "OK" if parameters are correct.
  There is no need to check if the device is voice capable/enabled or not.
  => ATS0, ATS1, ATS11
- A third set of AT commands, which contains some commands recently deleted by Altair
  => ATS3, ATS4, ATS5

comments.message: Why sometimes using tag __SWISTART__ / __SWISTOP__ and sometimes __SWI__?

Because there is no lines added. Typically for the modifications on 1 pre-existing line. I think that a START without STOP could be confusing.
So: 
- START / STOP if the moficiation can be bordered
- SWI for a "simple" modification on an existing line.

Merge traceability purpose: What do you think of

if [ -f $NVM_CFG_PATH/version ]; then
	VER_NVM=`uci -c $NVM_CFG_PATH get version.Config.Ver`

	#__SWISTART__
	# add test with SWIVER_NVM
	SWIVER_NVM=`uci -c $NVM_CFG_PATH get version.Config.SWIVer`
	#__SWISTOP__

	if [ "$VER_FS" != "$VER_NVM" ]
	then
		CFG_CP='true'
	fi

	#__SWISTART__
	if [ "$SWIVER_FS" != "$SWIVER_NVM" ]
	then
		CFG_CP='true'
	fi
	#__SWISTOP__

else

It's typically that I don't want do do in a simple case like here. 

For 1 added variable, there are 2 lines added (1 comment, 1 code) and 1 code lide modified. 
In your proposition, there are 10 lines added. 

The ratio seems to me very bad. It would be different if there are a lot of new variable, or a very complex instruction. But for a if?

But, if you think that the initial proposition is not possible for you, I can change it.

[Cosmetic] Some tabulations added: do on purpose?

Why sometimes using tag __SWISTART__ / __SWISTOP__ and sometimes __SWI__?
Don't ask me why make use tabulations. It's the make grammar, so I put tabulations because make wants it.
Like "NQ", this value could be put outside makefile, in the tags file

Absolutely. I thought about this possibilitie, but the probabilitie to have an other product than a HL77xx on this git repo is low (maybe I'm wrong...).
In this case, it is not very essential to have this string as an external.
But, if you want, I don't have an objection to put it outside the makefile.
Please tell me.
